# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acritarch
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acritarch/acid] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:acritarch/acid] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:acritarch/acid] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:acritarch/acid] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:acritarch/acid] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:acritarch/acid] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:acritarch/acid] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:acritarch/acid] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:acritarch/acid] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:acritarch/acid] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:acritarch/acid] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:acritarch/acid] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:acritarch/acid] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:acritarch/acid] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:acritarch/acid] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:acritarch/acid] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:acritarch/acid] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:acritarch/acid] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:acritarch/acid] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:acritarch/acid] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:acritarch/acid] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:acritarch/acid] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:acritarch/acid] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:acritarch/acid] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:acritarch/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:acritarch/acid] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:acritarch/acid] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:acritarch/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:acritarch/acid] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:acritarch/acid] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:acritarch/acid] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:acritarch/acid] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:acritarch/acid] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:acritarch/acid] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:acritarch/acid] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:acritarch/acid] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:acritarch/acid] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:acritarch/acid] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:acritarch/acid] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:acritarch/acid] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:acritarch/acid] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:acritarch/acid] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:acritarch/acid] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:acritarch/acid] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:acritarch/acid] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:acritarch/acid] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:acritarch/acid] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:acritarch/acid] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:acritarch/acid] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:acritarch/acid] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:acritarch/acid] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:acritarch/acid] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:acritarch/acid] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:acritarch/acid] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:acritarch/acid] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:acritarch/acid] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:acritarch/acid] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:acritarch/acid] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:acritarch/acid] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:acritarch/acid] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:acritarch/acid] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:acritarch/acid] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:acritarch/acid] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:acritarch/acid] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:acritarch/acid] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:acritarch/acid] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:acritarch/acid] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:acritarch/acid] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:acritarch/acid] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:acritarch/acid] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:acritarch/acid] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:acritarch/acid] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:acritarch/acid] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:acritarch/acid] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:acritarch/acid] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:acritarch/acid] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:acritarch/acid] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:acritarch/acid] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:acritarch/acid] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:acritarch/acid] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:acritarch/acid] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:acritarch/acid] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:acritarch/acid] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:acritarch/acid] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:acritarch/acid] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:acritarch/acid] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:acritarch/acid] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:acritarch/acid] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:acritarch/acid] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:acritarch/acid] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:acritarch/acid] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:acritarch/acid] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:acritarch/acid] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:acritarch/acid] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:acritarch/acid] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:acritarch/acid] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:acritarch/acid] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:acritarch/acid] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:acritarch/acid] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:acritarch/acid] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:acritarch/acid] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:acritarch/acid] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:acritarch/acid] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:acritarch/acid] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:acritarch/acid] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:acritarch/acid] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:acritarch/acid] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:acritarch/acid] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:acritarch/acid] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:acritarch/acid] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:acritarch/acid] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:acritarch/acid] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:acritarch/acid] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:acritarch/acid] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:acritarch/acid] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:acritarch/acid] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:acritarch/acid] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:acritarch/acid] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:acritarch/acid] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:acritarch/acid] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:acritarch/acid] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:acritarch/acid] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:acritarch/acid] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:acritarch/acid] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:acritarch/acid] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:acritarch/acid] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:acritarch/acid] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:acritarch/acid] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:acritarch/acid] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:acritarch/acid] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:acritarch/acid] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:acritarch/acid] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:acritarch/acid] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:acritarch/acid] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:acritarch/acid] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:acritarch/acid] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:acritarch/acid] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:acritarch/acid] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:acritarch/acid] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:acritarch/acid] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:acritarch/acid] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:acritarch/acid] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:acritarch/acid] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:acritarch/acid] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:acritarch/acid] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:acritarch/acid] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:acritarch/acid] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:acritarch/acid] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:acritarch/acid] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:acritarch/acid] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:acritarch/acid] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:acritarch/acid] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:acritarch/acid] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:acritarch/acid] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:acritarch/acid] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:acritarch/acid] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:acritarch/acid] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:acritarch/acid] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:acritarch/acid] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:acritarch/acid] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:acritarch/acid] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:acritarch/acid] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:acritarch/acid] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:acritarch/acid] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:acritarch/acid] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:acritarch/acid] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:acritarch/acid] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:acritarch/acid] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:acritarch/acid] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:acritarch/acid] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:acritarch/acid] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:acritarch/acid] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:acritarch/acid] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:acritarch/acid] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:acritarch/acid] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:acritarch/acid] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:acritarch/acid] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:acritarch/acid] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:acritarch/acid] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:acritarch/acid] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:acritarch/acid] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:acritarch/acid] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:acritarch/acid] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:acritarch/acid] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:acritarch/acid] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:acritarch/acid] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:acritarch/acid] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:acritarch/acid] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:acritarch/acid] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:acritarch/acid] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:acritarch/acid] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:acritarch/acid] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:acritarch/acid] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:acritarch/acid] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:acritarch/acid] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:acritarch/acid] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:acritarch/acid] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:acritarch/acid] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:acritarch/acid] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:acritarch/acid] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:acritarch/acid] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:acritarch/acid] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:acritarch/acid] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:acritarch/acid] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:acritarch/acid] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:acritarch/acid] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:acritarch/acid] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:acritarch/acid] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:acritarch/acid] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:acritarch/acid] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:acritarch/acid] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:acritarch/acinetactis] The validity and classification of this genus is contested.
[src:acritarch/acinetactis] In 1914, Adolf Pascher cast doubt on *Acinetactis*, suggesting that it was a junior synonym of *Dimorpha mutans*.
[src:acritarch/acinetactis] Cavalier-Smith classified *Acinetactis* as a heliomonad in 1993.
[src:acritarch/acinetactis] Bass et al. suggested in 2009 that the genus was a cercozoan in the class Granofilosea.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] Acritarchs were originally defined as non-acid soluble (i.e. non-carbonate, non-siliceous) organic-walled microfossils consisting of a central cavity, and whose biological affinities cannot be determined with certainty.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] Most commonly they are composed of thermally altered acid-insoluble carbon compounds (kerogen).
[src:acritarch/acritarch] Acritarchs may include the remains of a wide range of quite different kinds of organisms—ranging from the egg cases of small metazoans to resting cysts of many kinds of chlorophyta (green algae).
[src:acritarch/acritarch] It is likely that most acritarch species from the Paleozoic represent various stages of the life cycle of algae that were ancestral to the dinoflagellates.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] The nature of the organisms associated with Precambrian acritarchs is generally not well understood, though many are probably related to unicellular marine algae.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] In theory, when the biological source (taxon) of an acritarch does become known, that particular microfossil is removed from the acritarchs and classified with its proper group.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] While the classification of acritarchs into form genera is entirely artificial, it is not without merit, as the form taxa show traits similar to those of genuine taxa—for example an 'explosion' in the Cambrian and a mass extinction at the end of the Permian.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] The informal group Acritarcha Evitt 1963 was originally divided into these Subgroups: Acanthomorphitae, Polygonomorphitae, Prismatomorphitae, Oömorphitae, Netromorphitae, Dinetromorphitae, Stephanomorphitae, Pteromorphitae, Herkomorphitae, Platymorphitae, Sphaeromorphitae, and Disphaeromorphitae.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] In the end, it may well be, as Moczydłowska et al. suggested in 2011, that many acritarchs will, in fact, turn out to be algae.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] Acritarchs are found in sedimentary rocks from the present back into the Archean.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] They are typically isolated from siliciclastic sedimentary rocks using hydrofluoric acid but are occasionally extracted from carbonate-rich rocks.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] They are excellent candidates for index fossils used for dating rock formations in the Paleozoic Era and when other fossils are not available.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] Because most acritarchs are thought to be marine (pre-Triassic), they are also useful for palaeoenvironmental interpretation.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] The Archean and earliest Proterozoic microfossils termed "acritarchs" may actually be prokaryotes.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] The earliest eukaryotic acritarchs known (as of 2020) are from between 1950 and 2150 million years ago.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] At about 1 billion years ago the organisms responsible for acritarchs started to increase in abundance, diversity, size, complexity of shape, and especially, the size and number of spines.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] Their populations crashed during periods of extensive worldwide glaciations that covered the majority of the planet, but they proliferated in the Cambrian explosion and reached their highest diversity in the Paleozoic.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] The increased spininess 1000 million years ago possibly resulted from the need for defense against predators, especially predators large enough to swallow them or tear them apart.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] Other groups of small organisms from the Neoproterozoic era also show signs of anti-predator defenses.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] Further evidence that acritarchs were subject to herbivory around this time comes from a consideration of taxon longevity.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] Approximately 1,000 million years ago, species longevity fell sharply, suggesting that predation pressure, probably by protist herbivores, became an important factor.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] Predation would have kept populations in check, meaning that some nutrients were left unused, and new niches were available for new species to occupy.
[src:acritarch/acritarch] There are over 900 described genera; the following is a partial list, from Fossilid.info.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] The **actinophryids** are an order of heliozoa, a polyphyletic array of amoebae.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] They are common in fresh water and occasionally found in marine and soil habitats.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Actinophryids are unicellular and roughly spherical in shape, with many axopodia that radiate outward from the cell body.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Axopodia are a type of pseudopodia that are supported by hundreds of microtubules arranged in interlocking spirals and forming a needle-like internal structure or axoneme.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Small granules, extrusomes, that lie under the membrane of the body and axopodia capture flagellates, ciliates and small metazoa that make contact with the arms.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Actinophryids are largely aquatic protozoa with a spherical cell body and many needle-like axopodia.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] They resemble the shape of a sun due to this structure, which is the inspiration for their common name: heliozoa, or "sun-animalcules".
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Their bodies, without arms, range in size from a few tens of micrometers to slightly under a millimeter across.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] The outer region of cell body is often vacuolated.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] The endoplasm of actinophryids is less vacuolated than the outer layer, and a sharp boundary layer may be seen by light microscopy.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] The organisms can be either mononucleate, with a single, well defined nucleus in the center of the cell body, or multinucleate, with 10 or more nuclei located under the outer vacuolated layer of cytoplasm.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] The cytoplasm of actinophryids is often granular, similar to that of *Amoeba*.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Actinophryid cells may fuse when feeding, creating larger aggregated organisms.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Fine granules that occur just under the cell membrane are used up when food vacuoles form to enclose prey.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Actinophryids may also form cysts when food is not readily available.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] A layer of siliceous plates is deposited under the cell membrane during the encystment process.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Contractile vacuoles are common in these organisms, which are presumed to use them to maintain body volume by expelling fluids to compensate for the entry of water by osmosis.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Contractile vacuoles are visible as clear bulges from the surface of the cell body that slowly fill then rapidly deflate, expelling their contents into the environment.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] The most distinctive characteristic of the actinophryids is their axopodia.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] These axopodia consist of a central, rigid rod which is coated in a thin layer of ectoplasm.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] In *Actinophrys* the axonemes end on the surface of the central nucleus, and in the multicellular *Actinosphaerium* they end at or near nuclei.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] The axonemes are composed of microtubules arranged in a double spiral pattern characteristic of the order.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Due to their long, parallel construction, these microtubules demonstrate strong birefringence.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] These axopodia are used for prey capture, in movement, cell fusion and perhaps division.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] They are stiff but may flex especially near their tips, and are highly dynamic, undergoing frequent construction and destruction.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] When used to collect prey items, two methods of capture have been noted, termed axopodial flow and rapid axopodial contraction.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Axopodial flow involves the slow movement of a prey item along the surface of the axopod as the ectoplasm itself moves, while rapid axopodial contraction involves the collapse of the axoneme's microtubule structure.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] This behavior has been documented in many species, including *Actinosphaerium nucleofilum*, *Actinophrys sol*, and *Raphidiophrys contractilis*.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] The rapid axopodial contraction occurs at high speed, often in excess of 5mm/s or tens of body lengths per second.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] The axopodial contractions have been shown to be highly sensitive to environmental factors such as temperature and pressure as well as chemical signals like Ca2+ and colchicine.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Reproduction in actinophryids generally takes place via fission, where one parent cell divides into two or more daughter cells.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] For multinucleate heliozoa, this process is plasmotomic as the nuclei are not duplicated prior to division.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] It has been observed that reproduction appears to be a response to food scarcity, with an increased number of divisions following the removal of food and larger organisms during times of food excess.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Actinophryids also undergo autogamy during times of food scarcity.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] This is better described as genetic reorganization than reproduction, as the number of individuals produced is the same as the initial number.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Nonetheless, it serves as a way to increase genetic diversity within an individual which may improve the likelihood of expressing favorable genetic traits.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Plastogamy has also been extensively documented in actinophryids, especially in multinucleate ones.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] *Actinosphaerium* were observed to combine freely without the combination of nuclei, and this process sometimes resulted in more or less individuals than originally combined.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] This process is not caused merely by contact between two individuals but can be caused by damage to the cell body.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Under unfavourable conditions, some species will form a cyst.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] This is often the product of autogamy, in which case the cysts produced are zygotes.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Cells undergoing this process withdraw their axopodia, adhere to the substrate, and take on an opaque and grayish appearance.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] This cyst then divides until only uninucleate cells remain.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] The cyst wall is thickly layered 7–8 times and includes gelatinous layers, layers of silica plates, and iron.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Originally placed in Heliozoa (Sarcodina), the actinophryids are now understood to be part of the stramenopiles.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] They are unrelated to centrohelid and desmothoracid heliozoa with which they had been previously classified.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] There are several genera included within this classification.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] *Actinophrys* are smaller and have a single, central nucleus.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] Most have a cell body 40–50 micrometer in diameter with axopods around 100 μm in length, though this varies significantly.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] *Actinosphaerium* are several times larger, from 200 to 1000 μm in diameter, with many nuclei and are found exclusively in fresh water.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] A third genus, *Camptonema*, has a debated status.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] It has been observed once and was treated as a junior subjective synonym of *Actinosphaerium* by Mikrjukov & Patterson in 2001, but as a valid genus by Cavalier-Smith & Scoble (2013).
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] *Heliorapha* is a further debated taxon, it being a new generic vehicle for the species *azurina* that was initially assigned to the genus *Ciliophrys*.
[src:acritarch/actinophryid] According to the latest review of actinophryid classifications, they are organized into two genera and six species.
[src:acritarch/alga] Algae are polyphyletic as they have multiple evolutionary origins.
[src:acritarch/alga] Although algae with two-membraned chloroplasts seem to form a paraphyletic group within the clade Archaeplastida, other algae with chloroplasts that have three or more membranes evolved from protists that acquired photosynthesis after engulfing archaeplastids.
[src:acritarch/alga] Most algae are single-celled organisms without roots, leaves, or stems.
[src:acritarch/alga] Most are photoautotrophs and the main primary producers of aquatic ecosystems, although some are mixotrophs that derive metabolic energy both from internal photosynthesis and from foraging external nutrients.
[src:acritarch/alga] Some unicellular algae have become heterotrophs or parasites, relying entirely on external energy sources.
[src:acritarch/alga] Algae have photosynthetic machinery ultimately derived from cyanobacteria that produce oxygen by splitting water molecules, unlike photosynthetic bacteria.
[src:acritarch/alga] Fossilized filamentous algae from the Vindhya basin have been dated to 1.6 to 1.7 billion years ago.
[src:acritarch/alga] Because of the wide range of types of algae, there is a correspondingly wide range of industrial and traditional applications in human society.
[src:acritarch/alga] Traditional seaweed farming practices have existed for thousands of years and have strong traditions in East Asian food cultures.
[src:acritarch/alga] More modern algaculture applications extend the food traditions for other applications, including cattle feed, using algae for bioremediation or pollution control, transforming sunlight into algae fuels or other chemicals used in industrial processes, and in medical and scientific applications.
[src:acritarch/alga] The singular *alga* is the Latin word for "seaweed" and retains that meaning in English.
[src:acritarch/alga] Although some speculate that it is related to Latin *algēre*, "be cold", no reason is known to associate seaweed with temperature.
[src:acritarch/alga] A more likely source is *alliga*, "binding, entwining".
[src:acritarch/alga] The Ancient Greek word for "seaweed" was φῦκος (*phŷkos*), which could mean either the seaweed (probably red algae) or a red dye derived from it.
[src:acritarch/alga] The Latinization, *fūcus*, meant primarily the cosmetic rouge.
[src:acritarch/alga] The etymology is uncertain, but a strong candidate has long been some word related to the Biblical פוך (*pūk*), "paint" (if not that word itself), a cosmetic eye-shadow used by the Ancient Egyptians and other inhabitants of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:acritarch/alga] It could be any color: black, red, green, or blue.
[src:acritarch/alga] The study of algae is most commonly called phycology (from Greek *phykos* 'seaweed'); the term algology is falling out of use.
[src:acritarch/alga] The algae are a heterogeneous group of mostly photosynthetic organisms that produce oxygen and lack the reproductive features and structural complexity of land plants.
[src:acritarch/alga] This concept includes the cyanobacteria, which are prokaryotes, and all photosynthetic protists, which are eukaryotes.
[src:acritarch/alga] They contain chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment, and generally inhabit aquatic environments.
[src:acritarch/alga] However, there are many exceptions to this definition.
[src:acritarch/alga] Many non-photosynthetic protists are included in the study of algae, such as the heterotrophic relatives of euglenophytes or the numerous species of colorless algae that have lost their chlorophyll during evolution (e.g., *Prototheca*).
[src:acritarch/alga] Some exceptional species of algae tolerate dry terrestrial habitats, such as soil, rocks, or caves hidden from light sources, although they still need enough moisture to become active.
[src:acritarch/alga] A range of algal morphologies is exhibited, and convergence of features in unrelated groups is common.
[src:acritarch/alga] The only groups to exhibit three-dimensional multicellular thalli are the reds and browns, and some chlorophytes.
[src:acritarch/alga] Apical growth is constrained to subsets of these groups: the florideophyte reds, various browns, and the charophytes.
[src:acritarch/alga] The form of charophytes is quite different from those of reds and browns, because they have distinct nodes, separated by internode 'stems'; whorls of branches reminiscent of the horsetails occur at the nodes.
[src:acritarch/alga] Conceptacles are another polyphyletic trait; they appear in the coralline algae and the Hildenbrandiales, as well as the browns.
[src:acritarch/alga] Most of the simpler algae are unicellular flagellates or amoeboids, but colonial and nonmotile forms have developed independently among several of the groups.
[src:acritarch/alga] In three lines, even higher levels of organization have been reached, with full tissue differentiation.
[src:acritarch/alga] These are the brown algae,—some of which may reach 50 m in length (kelps)—the red algae, and the green algae.
[src:acritarch/alga] The most complex forms are found among the charophyte algae (see Charales and Charophyta), in a lineage that eventually led to the higher land plants.
[src:acritarch/alga] The innovation that defines these nonalgal plants is the presence of female reproductive organs with protective cell layers that protect the zygote and developing embryo.
[src:acritarch/alga] Hence, the land plants are referred to as the Embryophytes.
[src:acritarch/alga] The term algal turf is commonly used but poorly defined.
[src:acritarch/alga] Algal turfs are thick, carpet-like beds of seaweed that retain sediment and compete with foundation species like corals and kelps, and they are usually less than 15 cm tall.
[src:acritarch/alga] Such a turf may consist of one or more species, and will generally cover an area in the order of a square metre or more.
[src:acritarch/alga] Many algae, particularly species of the Characeae, have served as model experimental organisms to understand the mechanisms of the water permeability of membranes, osmoregulation, salt tolerance, cytoplasmic streaming, and the generation of action potentials.
[src:acritarch/alga] Plant hormones are found not only in higher plants, but in algae, too.
[src:acritarch/alga] Rhodophyta, Chlorophyta, and Heterokontophyta, the three main algal divisions, have life cycles which show considerable variation and complexity.
[src:acritarch/alga] In general, an asexual phase exists where the seaweed's cells are diploid, a sexual phase where the cells are haploid, followed by fusion of the male and female gametes.
[src:acritarch/alga] Asexual reproduction permits efficient population increases, but less variation is possible.
[src:acritarch/alga] Commonly, in sexual reproduction of unicellular and colonial algae, two specialized, sexually compatible, haploid gametes make physical contact and fuse to form a zygote.
[src:acritarch/alga] To ensure a successful mating, the development and release of gametes is highly synchronized and regulated; pheromones may play a key role in these processes.
[src:acritarch/alga] Sexual reproduction allows for more variation and provides the benefit of efficient recombinational repair of DNA damage during meiosis, a key stage of the sexual cycle.
[src:acritarch/alga] However, sexual reproduction is more costly than asexual reproduction.
[src:acritarch/alga] Meiosis has been shown to occur in many different species of algae.
[src:acritarch/alga] Linnaeus, in *Species Plantarum* (1753), the starting point for modern botanical nomenclature, recognized 14 genera of algae, of which only four are currently considered among algae.
[src:acritarch/alga] In *Systema Naturae*, Linnaeus described the genera *Volvox* and *Corallina*, and a species of *Acetabularia* (as *Madrepora*), among the animals.
[src:acritarch/alga] In 1768, Samuel Gottlieb Gmelin (1744–1774) published the *Historia Fucorum*, the first work dedicated to marine algae and the first book on marine biology to use the then new binomial nomenclature of Linnaeus.
[src:acritarch/alga] It included elaborate illustrations of seaweed and marine algae on folded leaves.
[src:acritarch/alga] Harvey (1811–1866) and Lamouroux (1813) were the first to divide macroscopic algae into four divisions based on their pigmentation.
[src:acritarch/alga] This is the first use of a biochemical criterion in plant systematics.
[src:acritarch/alga] Harvey's four divisions are: red algae (Rhodospermae), brown algae (Melanospermae), green algae (Chlorospermae), and Diatomaceae.
[src:acritarch/alga] At this time, microscopic algae were discovered and reported by a different group of workers (e.g., O.
[src:acritarch/alga] Müller and Ehrenberg) studying the Infusoria (microscopic organisms).
[src:acritarch/alga] Unlike macroalgae, which were clearly viewed as plants, microalgae were frequently considered animals because they are often motile.
[src:acritarch/alga] Even the nonmotile (coccoid) microalgae were sometimes merely seen as stages of the lifecycle of plants, macroalgae, or animals.
[src:acritarch/alga] Although used as a taxonomic category in some pre-Darwinian classifications, e.g., Linnaeus (1753), de Jussieu (1789), Lamouroux (1813), Harvey (1836), Horaninow (1843), Agassiz (1859), Wilson & Cassin (1864), in further classifications, the "algae" are seen as an artificial, polyphyletic group.
[src:acritarch/alga] Throughout the 20th century, most classifications treated the following groups as divisions or classes of algae: cyanophytes, rhodophytes, chrysophytes, xanthophytes, bacillariophytes, phaeophytes, pyrrhophytes (cryptophytes and dinophytes), euglenophytes, and chlorophytes.
[src:acritarch/alga] With the abandonment of plant-animal dichotomous classification, most groups of algae (sometimes all) were included in Protista, later also abandoned in favour of Eukaryota.
[src:acritarch/alga] However, as a legacy of the older plant life scheme, some groups that were also treated as protozoans in the past still have duplicated classifications (see ambiregnal protists).
[src:acritarch/alga] In other cases, some groups were originally characterized as parasitic algae (e.g., *Chlorochytrium*), but later were seen as endophytic algae.
[src:acritarch/alga] Some filamentous bacteria (e.g., *Beggiatoa*) were originally seen as algae.
[src:acritarch/alga] Furthermore, groups like the apicomplexans are also parasites derived from ancestors that possessed plastids, but are not included in any group traditionally seen as algae.
[src:acritarch/alga] The most recent estimate (as of January 2024) documents 50,605 living and 10,556 fossil algal species, according to the online database AlgaeBase.
[src:acritarch/alga] They are classified into 15 phyla or divisions.
[src:acritarch/alga] Some phyla are not photosynthetic, namely Picophyta and Rhodelphidophyta, but they are included in the database due to their close relationship with red algae.
[src:acritarch/alga] The various algal phyla can be differentiated according to several biological traits.
[src:acritarch/alga] They have distinct morphologies, photosynthetic pigmentation, storage products, cell wall composition, and mechanisms of carbon concentration.
[src:acritarch/alga] Some phyla have unique cellular structures.
[src:acritarch/alga] , the most common genus of cyanobacteria.
[src:acritarch/alga] Among prokaryotes, five major groups of bacteria have evolved the ability to photosynthesize, including heliobacteria, green sulfur and nonsulfur bacteria and proteobacteria.
[src:acritarch/alga] However, the only lineage where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved is in the cyanobacteria, often known as blue-green algae for their blue-green (cyan) coloration.
[src:acritarch/alga] They are classified as the phylum Cyanobacteriota or Cyanophyta.
[src:acritarch/alga] However, this phylum also includes two classes of non-photosynthetic bacteria: Melainabacteria (also called Vampirovibrionia or Vampirovibrionophyceae) and Sericytochromatia (also known as Blackallbacteria).
[src:acritarch/alga] A third class contains the photosynthetic ones, known as Cyanophyceae (also called Cyanobacteriia or Oxyphotobacteria).
[src:acritarch/alga] As bacteria, their cells lack membrane-bound organelles, with the exception of thylakoids.
[src:acritarch/alga] Like other algae, cyanobacteria have chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment.
[src:acritarch/alga] Their accessory pigments include phycobilins (phycoerythrobilin and phycocyanobilin), carotenoids and, in some cases, *b*, *d*, or *f* chlorophylls, generally distributed in phycobilisomes found in the surface of thylakoids.
[src:acritarch/alga] They display a variety of body forms, such as single cells, colonies, and unbranched or branched filaments.
[src:acritarch/alga] Their cells are commonly covered in a sheath of mucilage, and they also have a typical gram-negative bacterial cell wall composed largely of peptidoglycan.
[src:acritarch/alga] They have various storage particles, including cyanophycin as aminoacid and nitrogen reserves, "cyanophycean starch" (similar to plant amylose) for carbohydrates, and lipid droplets.
[src:acritarch/alga] Their Rubisco enzymes are concentrated in carboxysomes.
[src:acritarch/alga] They occupy a diverse array of aquatic and terrestrial habitats, including extreme environments from hot springs to polar glaciers.
[src:acritarch/alga] Some are subterranean, living via hydrogen-based lithoautotrophy instead of photosynthesis.
[src:acritarch/alga] Three lineages of cyanobacteria, *Prochloraceae*, *Prochlorothrix* and *Prochlorococcus*, independently evolved to have chlorophylls *a* and *b* instead of phycobilisomes.
[src:acritarch/alga] Due to their different pigmentation, they were historically grouped in a separate division, Prochlorophyta, as this is the typical pigmentation seen in green algae (e.g., chlorophytes).
[src:acritarch/alga] Eventually, this classification became obsolete, as it is a polyphyletic grouping.
[src:acritarch/alga] Cyanobacteria are included as algae by most phycological sources and by the International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants, although a few authors exclude them from the definition of algae and reserve the term for eukaryotes only.
[src:acritarch/alga] Eukaryotic algae contain chloroplasts that are similar in structure to cyanobacteria.
[src:acritarch/alga] Chloroplasts contain circular DNA like that in cyanobacteria and are interpreted as representing reduced endosymbiotic cyanobacteria.
[src:acritarch/alga] However, the exact origin of the chloroplasts is different among separate lineages of algae, reflecting their acquisition during different endosymbiotic events.
[src:acritarch/alga] Many groups contain some members that are no longer photosynthetic.
[src:acritarch/alga] Some retain plastids, but not chloroplasts, while others have lost plastids entirely.
[src:acritarch/alga] Primary algae are those with "primary chloroplasts", i.e. chloroplasts with two membranes, evolved through a single symbiogenetic event with an endosymbiont β-cyanobacterium as early as 1.6 Gya during the Mesoproterozoic.
[src:acritarch/alga] These algae are mainly grouped in the clade Archaeplastida (meaning "ancient plastid"), which includes the major groups Viridiplantae (green algae *sensu lato* and all land plants) and Rhodophyta (red algae) as well as the minor group Glaucophyta (grey algae).
[src:acritarch/alga] Land plants (embryophytes) are pigmented similarly to green algae and likely evolved from the freshwater green algae clade Streptophyta, which is sister taxon to Chlorophyta (green algae *sensu stricto*) and the basal clade Prasinodermophyta.
[src:acritarch/alga] There is also a minor group of amoeboid protists with primary plastids evolved via different origin and at a much later date than archaeplastid chloroplasts.
[src:acritarch/alga] The four species of the euglyphid amoebae genus *Paulinella*, have cyanobionts (known as cyanelles) that perform photosynthesis, likely originated from the endosymbiosis of a α-cyanobacterium (probably an ancestral member of Chroococcales), about 90–140 Mya during the Cretaceous.
[src:acritarch/alga] Secondary algae are eukaryotes with "secondary chloroplasts", i.e. those evolved from phagocytosis and subsequent endosymbiosis of primary algae (mainly green or red algae) or other secondary algae, thus "stealing" the endosymbionts' photosynthetic capability.
[src:acritarch/alga] As a result, these algae have chloroplasts surrounded by three or more membranes, and appeared independently in various distantly related protist lineages.
[src:acritarch/alga] Two lineages of secondary algae, chlorarachniophytes and euglenophytes have "green" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *b*.
[src:acritarch/alga] Their chloroplasts are surrounded by four and three membranes, respectively, and were probably retained from ingested green algae.
[src:acritarch/alga] Other groups have "red" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *c*, and phycobilins.
[src:acritarch/alga] The shape can vary; they may be of discoid, plate-like, reticulate, cup-shaped, spiral, or ribbon shaped.
[src:acritarch/alga] They have one or more pyrenoids to preserve protein and starch.
[src:acritarch/alga] The latter chlorophyll type is not known from any prokaryotes or primary chloroplasts, but genetic similarities with red algae suggest a relationship there.
[src:acritarch/alga] The typical dinoflagellate chloroplast has three membranes, but considerable diversity exists in chloroplasts within the group, and a number of endosymbiotic events apparently occurred.
[src:acritarch/alga] The Apicomplexa, a group of closely related parasites, also have plastids called apicoplasts, which are not photosynthetic.
[src:acritarch/alga] The Chromerida are the closest relatives of apicomplexans, and some have retained their chloroplasts.
[src:acritarch/alga] The three alveolate groups evolved from a common myzozoan ancestor that obtained chloroplasts.
[src:acritarch/alga] The distribution of algal species has been fairly well studied since the founding of phytogeography in the mid-19th century.
[src:acritarch/alga] Algae spread mainly by the dispersal of spores analogously to the dispersal of cryptogamic plants by spores.
[src:acritarch/alga] Spores can be found in a variety of environments: fresh and marine waters, air, soil, and in or on other organisms.
[src:acritarch/alga] Whether a spore is to grow into an adult organism depends on the species and the environmental conditions where the spore lands.
[src:acritarch/alga] The spores of freshwater algae are dispersed mainly by running water and wind, as well as by living carriers.
[src:acritarch/alga] However, not all bodies of water can carry all species of algae, as the chemical composition of certain water bodies limits the algae that can survive within them.
[src:acritarch/alga] Marine spores are often spread by ocean currents.
[src:acritarch/alga] Ocean water presents many vastly different habitats based on temperature and nutrient availability, resulting in phytogeographic zones, regions, and provinces.
[src:acritarch/alga] To some degree, the distribution of algae is subject to floristic discontinuities caused by geographical features, such as Antarctica, long distances of ocean or general land masses.
[src:acritarch/alga] It is, therefore, possible to identify species occurring by locality, such as "Pacific algae" or "North Sea algae".
[src:acritarch/alga] When they occur out of their localities, hypothesizing a transport mechanism is usually possible, such as the hulls of ships.
[src:acritarch/alga] For example, *Ulva reticulata* and *U. fasciata* travelled from the mainland to Hawaii in this manner.
[src:acritarch/alga] Mapping is possible for select species only: "there are many valid examples of confined distribution patterns." For example, *Clathromorphum* is an arctic genus and is not mapped far south of there.
[src:acritarch/alga] For example, according to one standard textbook, in the British Isles, the *UK Biodiversity Steering Group Report* estimated there to be 20,000 algal species in the UK.
[src:acritarch/alga] Another checklist reports only about 5,000 species.
[src:acritarch/alga] and so on, but lacking any scientific basis or reliable sources, these numbers have no more credibility than the British ones mentioned above.
[src:acritarch/alga] Most estimates also omit microscopic algae, such as phytoplankton.
[src:acritarch/alga] Algae are prominent in bodies of water, common in terrestrial environments, and are found in unusual environments, such as on snow and ice.
[src:acritarch/alga] Seaweeds grow mostly in shallow marine waters, less than 100 m (330 ft) deep; however, some such as *Navicula pennata* have been recorded to a depth of 360 m (1,180 ft).
[src:acritarch/alga] A type of algae, *Ancylonema nordenskioeldii*, was found in Greenland in areas known as the 'Dark Zone', which caused an increase in the rate of melting ice sheet.
[src:acritarch/alga] The same algae was found in the Italian Alps, after pink ice appeared on parts of the Presena glacier.
[src:acritarch/alga] The various sorts of algae play significant roles in aquatic ecology.
[src:acritarch/alga] Microscopic forms that live suspended in the water column (phytoplankton) provide the food base for most marine food chains.
[src:acritarch/alga] In very high densities (algal blooms), these algae may discolor the water and outcompete, poison, or asphyxiate other life forms.
[src:acritarch/alga] Algae can be used as indicator organisms to monitor pollution in various aquatic systems.
[src:acritarch/alga] In many cases, algal metabolism is sensitive to various pollutants.
[src:acritarch/alga] Due to this, the species composition of algal populations may shift in the presence of chemical pollutants.
[src:acritarch/alga] To detect these changes, algae can be sampled from the environment and maintained in laboratories with relative ease.
[src:acritarch/alga] Some species of algae form symbiotic relationships with other organisms.
[src:acritarch/alga] In these symbioses, the algae supply photosynthates (organic substances) to the host organism providing protection to the algal cells.
[src:acritarch/alga] The host organism derives some or all of its energy requirements from the algae.
[src:acritarch/alga] Lichens are defined by the International Association for Lichenology to be "an association of a fungus and a photosynthetic symbiont resulting in a stable vegetative body having a specific structure".
[src:acritarch/alga] The fungi, or mycobionts, are mainly from the Ascomycota with a few from the Basidiomycota.
[src:acritarch/alga] In nature, they do not occur separate from lichens.
[src:acritarch/alga] It is unknown when they began to associate.
[src:acritarch/alga] One or more mycobiont associates with the same phycobiont species, from the green algae, except that alternatively, the mycobiont may associate with a species of cyanobacteria (hence "photobiont" is the more accurate term).
[src:acritarch/alga] A photobiont may be associated with many different mycobionts or may live independently; accordingly, lichens are named and classified as fungal species.
[src:acritarch/alga] The association is termed a morphogenesis because the lichen has a form and capabilities not possessed by the symbiont species alone (they can be experimentally isolated).
[src:acritarch/alga] The photobiont possibly triggers otherwise latent genes in the mycobiont.
[src:acritarch/alga] Trentepohlia is an example of a common green alga genus worldwide that can grow on its own or be lichenised.
[src:acritarch/alga] Lichen thus share some of the habitat and often similar appearance with specialized species of algae (*aerophytes*) growing on exposed surfaces such as tree trunks and rocks and sometimes discoloring them.
[src:acritarch/alga] Coral reefs are accumulated from the calcareous exoskeletons of marine invertebrates of the order Scleractinia (stony corals).
[src:acritarch/alga] These animals metabolize sugar and oxygen to obtain energy for their cell-building processes, including secretion of the exoskeleton, with water and carbon dioxide as byproducts.
[src:acritarch/alga] Dinoflagellates (algal protists) are often endosymbionts in the cells of the coral-forming marine invertebrates, where they accelerate host-cell metabolism by generating sugar and oxygen immediately available through photosynthesis using incident light and the carbon dioxide produced by the host.
[src:acritarch/alga] Reef-building stony corals (hermatypic corals) require endosymbiotic algae from the genus *Symbiodinium* to be in a healthy condition.
[src:acritarch/alga] The loss of *Symbiodinium* from the host is known as coral bleaching, a condition which leads to the deterioration of a reef.
[src:acritarch/alga] Endosymbiontic green algae live close to the surface of some sponges, for example, breadcrumb sponges (*Halichondria panicea*).
[src:acritarch/alga] The alga is thus protected from predators; the sponge is provided with oxygen and sugars which can account for 50 to 80% of sponge growth in some species.
[src:acritarch/alga] Prokaryotic algae, i.e., cyanobacteria, are the only group of organisms where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved.
[src:acritarch/alga] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of cyanobacteria is dated at 2100 million years ago, although stromatolites, associated with cyanobacterial biofilms, appear as early as 3500 million years ago in the fossil record.
[src:acritarch/alga] Eukaryotic algae are polyphyletic thus their origin cannot be traced back to a single hypothetical common ancestor.
[src:acritarch/alga] It is thought that they came into existence when photosynthetic coccoid cyanobacteria got phagocytized by a unicellular heterotrophic eukaryote (a protist), giving rise to double-membranous primary plastids.
[src:acritarch/alga] Such symbiogenic events (primary symbiogenesis) are believed to have occurred more than 1.5 billion years ago during the Calymmian period, early in Boring Billion, but it is difficult to track the key events because of so much time gap.
[src:acritarch/alga] This process of serial cell "capture" and "enslavement" explains the diversity of photosynthetic eukaryotes.
[src:acritarch/alga] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of eukaryotic algae is *Bangiomorpha pubescens*, a red alga found in rocks around 1047 million years old.
[src:acritarch/alga] Recent genomic and phylogenomic approaches have significantly clarified plastid genome evolution, the horizontal movement of endosymbiont genes to the "host" nuclear genome, and plastid spread throughout the eukaryotic tree of life.
[src:acritarch/alga] It is accepted that both euglenophytes and chlorarachniophytes obtained their chloroplasts from chlorophytes that became endosymbionts.
[src:acritarch/alga] In particular, euglenophyte chloroplasts share the most resemblance with the genus *Pyramimonas*.
[src:acritarch/alga] However, there is still no clear order in which the secondary and tertiary endosymbioses occurred for the "chromist" lineages (ochrophytes, cryptophytes, haptophytes and myzozoans).
[src:acritarch/alga] Two main models have been proposed to explain the order, both of which agree that cryptophytes obtained their chloroplasts from red algae.
[src:acritarch/alga] One model, hypothesized in 2014 by John W.
[src:acritarch/alga] Stiller and coauthors, suggests that a cryptophyte became the plastid of ochrophytes, which in turn became the plastid of myzozoans and haptophytes.
[src:acritarch/alga] The other model, suggested by Andrzej Bodył and coauthors in 2009, describes that a cryptophyte became the plastid of both haptophytes and ochrophytes, and it is a haptophyte that became the plastid of myzozoans instead.
[src:acritarch/alga] These charophyte algae probably already developed filamentous thalli and holdfasts that superficially resembled plant stems and roots, and probably had an isomorphic alternation of generations.
[src:acritarch/alga] They perhaps evolved some 850 mya and might even be as early as 1 Gya during the late phase of the Boring Billion.
[src:acritarch/alga] Algaculture is a form of aquaculture involving the farming of species of algae.
[src:acritarch/alga] The majority of algae that are intentionally cultivated fall into the category of microalgae (also referred to as phytoplankton, microphytes, or planktonic algae).
[src:acritarch/alga] Global production of farmed aquatic plants, overwhelmingly dominated by seaweeds, grew in output volume from 13.5 million tonnes in 1995, to just over 30 million tonnes in 2016 and 37.8 million tonnes in 2022 and 40 million tonnes in 2024.
[src:acritarch/alga] This increase was the result of production expansions led by China, followed by Malaysia, the Philippines, the United Republic of Tanzania, and the Russian Federation.
[src:acritarch/alga] Cultured microalgae already contribute to a wide range of sectors in the emerging bioeconomy.
[src:acritarch/alga] Research suggests there are large potentials and benefits of algaculture for the development of a future healthy and sustainable food system.
[src:acritarch/alga] Seaweed farming or kelp farming is the practice of cultivating and harvesting seaweed.
[src:acritarch/alga] In its simplest form farmers gather from natural beds, while at the other extreme farmers fully control the crop's life cycle.
[src:acritarch/alga] The seven most cultivated taxa are *Eucheuma* spp., *Kappaphycus alvarezii*, *Gracilaria* spp., *Saccharina japonica*, *Undaria pinnatifida*, *Pyropia* spp., and *Sargassum fusiforme*.
[src:acritarch/alga] *Eucheuma* and *K. alvarezii* are attractive for carrageenan (a gelling agent); *Gracilaria* is farmed for agar; the rest are eaten after limited processing.
[src:acritarch/alga] Seaweeds are different from mangroves and seagrasses, as they are photosynthetic algal organisms and are non-flowering.
[src:acritarch/alga] The largest seaweed-producing countries as of 2022 are China (58.62%) and Indonesia (28.6%); followed by South Korea (5.09%) and the Philippines (4.19%).
[src:acritarch/alga] Seaweed farming has frequently been developed to improve economic conditions and to reduce fishing pressure.
[src:acritarch/alga] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that world production in 2019 was over 35 million tonnes.
[src:acritarch/alga] North America produced some 23,000 tonnes of wet seaweed.
[src:acritarch/alga] Alaska, Maine, France, and Norway each more than doubled their seaweed production since 2018*.* As of 2019, seaweed represented 30% of marine aquaculture.
[src:acritarch/alga] In 2023, the global seaweed extract market was valued at $16.5 billion, with strong projected growth.
[src:acritarch/alga] Seaweed farming is a carbon negative crop, with a high potential for climate change mitigation.
[src:acritarch/alga] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" as a mitigation tactic.
[src:acritarch/alga] World Wildlife Fund, Oceans 2050, and The Nature Conservancy publicly support expanded seaweed cultivation.
[src:acritarch/alga] An algae bioreactor is used for cultivating micro or macroalgae.
[src:acritarch/alga] Algae may be cultivated for the purposes of biomass production (as in a seaweed cultivator), wastewater treatment, CO2 fixation, or aquarium/pond filtration in the form of an algae scrubber.
[src:acritarch/alga] Algae bioreactors vary widely in design, falling broadly into two categories: open reactors and enclosed reactors.
[src:acritarch/alga] Open reactors are exposed to the atmosphere while enclosed reactors, also commonly called photobioreactors, are isolated to varying extents from the atmosphere.
[src:acritarch/alga] Specifically, algae bioreactors can be used to produce fuels such as biodiesel and bioethanol, to generate animal feed, or to reduce pollutants such as NOx and CO2 in flue gases of power plants.
[src:acritarch/alga] Fundamentally, this kind of bioreactor is based on the photosynthetic reaction, which is performed by the chlorophyll-containing algae itself using dissolved carbon dioxide and sunlight.
[src:acritarch/alga] The carbon dioxide is dispersed into the reactor fluid to make it accessible to the algae.
[src:acritarch/alga] The bioreactor has to be made out of transparent material.
[src:acritarch/alga] To be competitive and independent from fluctuating support from (local) policy on the long run, biofuels should equal or beat the cost level of fossil fuels.
[src:acritarch/alga] Here, algae-based fuels hold great promise, directly related to the potential to produce more biomass per unit area in a year than any other form of biomass.
[src:acritarch/alga] The break-even point for algae-based biofuels is estimated to occur by 2025.
[src:acritarch/alga] Today, algae are used by humans in many ways; for example, as fertilizers, soil conditioners, and livestock feed.
[src:acritarch/alga] Aquatic and microscopic species are cultured in clear tanks or ponds and are either harvested or used to treat effluents pumped through the ponds.
[src:acritarch/alga] Algaculture on a large scale is an important type of aquaculture in some places.
[src:acritarch/alga] Maerl is commonly used as a soil conditioner.
[src:acritarch/alga] Algae are used as foods in many countries: China consumes more than 70 species, including *fat choy*, a cyanobacterium considered a vegetable; Japan, over 20 species such as *nori* and *aonori*; Ireland, dulse; Chile, cochayuyo.
[src:acritarch/alga] Laver is used to make laverbread in Wales, where it is known as *bara lawr*.
[src:acritarch/alga] In Korea, green laver is used to make *gim*.
[src:acritarch/alga] The oils from some algae have high levels of unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:acritarch/alga] Some varieties of algae favored by vegetarianism and veganism contain the long-chain, essential omega-3 fatty acids, docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) and eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA).
[src:acritarch/alga] Fish oil contains the omega-3 fatty acids, but the original source is algae (microalgae in particular), which are eaten by marine life such as copepods and are passed up the food chain.
[src:acritarch/alga] The natural pigments (carotenoids and chlorophylls) produced by algae can be used as alternatives to chemical dyes and coloring agents.
[src:acritarch/alga] Carrageenan, from the red alga *Chondrus crispus*, is used as a thickener and stabilizer in milk products.
[src:acritarch/alga] Agar, a gelatinous substance derived from red algae, has a number of commercial uses.
[src:acritarch/alga] It is a good medium on which to grow bacteria and fungi, as most microorganisms cannot digest agar.
[src:acritarch/alga] Alginic acid, or alginate, is extracted from brown algae.
[src:acritarch/alga] Its uses range from gelling agents in food, to medical dressings.
[src:acritarch/alga] Alginic acid also has been used in the field of biotechnology as a biocompatible medium for cell encapsulation and cell immobilization.
[src:acritarch/alga] Molecular cuisine is also a user of the substance for its gelling properties, by which it becomes a delivery vehicle for flavours.
[src:acritarch/alga] Between 100,000 and 170,000 wet tons of *Macrocystis* are harvested annually in New Mexico for alginate extraction and abalone feed.
[src:acritarch/alga] Agricultural Research Service scientists found that 60–90% of nitrogen runoff and 70–100% of phosphorus runoff can be captured from manure effluents using a horizontal algae scrubber, also called an algal turf scrubber (ATS).
[src:acritarch/alga] Scientists developed the ATS, which consists of shallow, 30-metre (100 ft) raceways of nylon netting where algae colonies can form, and studied its efficacy for three years.
[src:acritarch/alga] They found that algae can readily be used to reduce the nutrient runoff from agricultural fields and increase the quality of water flowing into rivers, streams, and oceans.
[src:acritarch/alga] Researchers collected and dried the nutrient-rich algae from the ATS and studied its potential as an organic fertilizer.
[src:acritarch/alga] They found that cucumber and corn seedlings grew just as well using ATS organic fertilizer as they did with commercial fertilizers.
[src:acritarch/alga] Algae scrubbers, using bubbling upflow or vertical waterfall versions, are now also being used to filter aquaria and ponds.
[src:acritarch/alga] The alga *Stichococcus bacillaris* has been seen to colonize silicone resins used at archaeological sites; biodegrading the synthetic substance.
[src:acritarch/alga] Various polymers can be created from algae, which can be especially useful in the creation of bioplastics.
[src:acritarch/alga] These include hybrid plastics, cellulose-based plastics, poly-lactic acid, and bio-polyethylene.
[src:acritarch/alga] Several companies have begun to produce algae polymers commercially, including for use in flip-flops and in surf boards.
[src:acritarch/alga] Even algae is also used to prepare various polymeric resins suitable for coating applications.
[src:acritarch/alga] The third island on Kunming Lake at Beijing's Summer Palace is called Zaojian Tang Dao (藻鑒堂島).
[src:acritarch/algaebase] AlgaeBase began in March 1996, founded by Michael Guiry.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] By 2005, the database contained about 65,000 names.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] In 2013, AlgaeBase and the Flanders Marine Institute (VLIZ) signed an end-user license agreement regarding the Electronic Intellectual Property of AlgaeBase.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] This allows the World Register of Marine Species (WoRMS) to include taxonomic names of algae in WoRMS, thereby allowing WoRMS, as part of the Aphia database, to make its overview of all described marine species more complete.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] After a long phase of further development and testing, the AlgaeBase harvester tool was implemented by the WoRMS data management team in early 2019.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] Since then, newly-added species in AlgaeBase are added to Aphia and, if marine, to WoRMS as well.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] The database is hosted at the National University of Ireland's Ryan Institute, in Galway.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] It includes about all types of algae, as well as one group of flowering plants, the sea-grasses.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] Information about each species' taxonomy, nomenclature and distribution is included, and the algae covered include terrestrial as well as marine and freshwater species, such as seaweeds, phytoplankton, and freshwater algae.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] As of 2019, marine species have the best coverage, including sea-grasses.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] As of 2014 there were nearly 17,000 images, and the database was being used by 2,000–3,000 individual visitors each day.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] As of 2023, there were about 170,000 species and infraspecies in AlgaeBase.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] The synchronisation between AlgaeBase and Aphia was possible through support of the LifeWatch Species Information Backbone.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] LifeWatch, the E-Science European Infrastructure for Biodiversity and Ecosystem Research, is a distributed virtual laboratory, which is used for different aspects of biodiversity research.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] As of 2022, the main sponsors of the database are the Phycological Society of America, the British Phycological Society, the International Phycological Society, and the Korean Phycological Society.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] Programming is carried out by Pier Kuipers and Caoilte Guiry, and Michael Guiry.
[src:acritarch/algaebase] Jonathan Guthrie was responsible for programming much of earlier versions.
[src:acritarch/algospongia] Algospongia (vernacular name: algosponges) is a taxon of calcified fossil organisms comprising around 90 accepted genera and several hundred species, treated taxonomically as a single class in an unspecified phylum.
[src:acritarch/algospongia] Originally considered to be fossil sponges or "pseudo algae", an assignment now refuted, their taxonomic position is somewhat unresolved.
[src:acritarch/algospongia] Of the three most prominent recent researchers, B.
[src:acritarch/algospongia] Mamet (Belgium) assigns certain families (e.g.
[src:acritarch/algospongia] Palaeoberesellaceae, Beresellaceae and Issinellaceae) to Chlorophyta (green algae) as an order of that phylum (Palaeosiphonocladales), at least one other family (Ungdarellaceae) to Rhodophyta (red algae), and some other genera (*Groenlandella*, *Labyrinthoconus*) simply to "Microproblematica".
[src:acritarch/algospongia] Cózar (Spain) treated Algospongia (such as the family Calcifoliaceae) as Algae *incertae sedis*, before deciding (in 2010) against any algal affinity and reassigning them to the [zoological] protists, as a group possibly paralleling the Foraminifera.
[src:acritarch/algospongia] Since that paper, Cózar has continued to use zoological terminology in his published works, while Vachard has once again assigned the group to the Algae *incertae sedis*, lying hypothetically mid-way between the extant Rhodophyta and Chlorophyta.
[src:acritarch/algospongia] A number of the genera allocated to Algospongia in the present treatment (which follows Vachard & Cózar, 2010 in the main) were recently (2021) treated as either Foraminifera, or as red or green algae, in the World Register of Marine Species, a situation that is currently under revision.
[src:acritarch/algospongia] Members of the group occur in the fossil record from the Ordovician to the Late Permian periods, although only *Wetheredella* is prominent prior to the start of the Devonian.
[src:acritarch/algospongia] Algosponges are described as a group of sessile or attached microorganisms with characteristic calcified walls described as "yellowish, apparently granular" that are frequently perforated, and possess either lateral or terminal apertures between successive chambers or cells.
[src:acritarch/algospongia] The treatment below is based on that published by Vachard & Cózar in 2010, (alternative, botanical treatment indicated separated by "/"); more recent genera (post 2010) and, in some cases, corrections have been added per other available sources.
[src:acritarch/algospongia] The possibly analogous Foraminifera (protists or Protozoa in many classifications) are members of the clade SAR, which is presently assigned to the kingdom Chromista in many classifications.
[src:acritarch/algospongia] The stratigraphic range of selected algosponge genera is summarised in Figure 15 of Vachard & Cózar (2010).
[src:acritarch/algospongia] From this Figure it is apparent that *Wetheredella* is the sole representative of the group from the Upper Ordovician through the Silurian, being joined by *Asphaltinoides* a little before the Silurian ends.
[src:acritarch/algospongia] The majority of other genera then develop within, and/or are restricted to, the Devonian through Carboniferous periods, with a relatively small number (16) persisting through the Permian before all becoming extinct by the end of that period.
[src:acritarch/algospongia] The same authors also comment (their "Conclusion" no.
[src:acritarch/algospongia] As mentioned above, members of the claimed single class Algospongia have been assigned to different taxonomic groups over time, with no clear consensus emerging.
